1
00:00:19,447 --> 00:00:22,678
[Clocks ticking]

2
00:01:26,527 --> 00:01:28,483
ANNOUNCER: <i>October is inventory time</i>.

3
00:01:28,567 --> 00:01:32,003
<i>So right now, Statler Toyota is making</i>
<i>the best deals of the year...</i>

4
00:01:32,087 --> 00:01:34,123
<i>... on all 1985-model Toyotas.</i>

5
00:01:34,207 --> 00:01:35,879
<i>You won't find a better car...</i>

6
00:01:35,967 --> 00:01:39,596
<i>... at a better price with better service</i>
<i>anywhere in Hill Valley.</i>

7
00:01:45,047 --> 00:01:47,766
NEWSCASTER: <i>The Senate is expected</i>
<i>to vote on this today.</i>

8
00:01:47,847 --> 00:01:51,999
<i>In other news, officials at</i>
<i>the Pacific Nuclear research facility...</i>

9
00:01:52,087 --> 00:01:54,965
<i>... have denied the rumor</i>
<i>that a case of missing plutonium...</i>

10
00:01:55,047 --> 00:01:57,800
<i>... was in fact stolen</i>
<i>from their vault two weeks ago.</i>

11
00:01:57,887 --> 00:02:01,516
<i>A Libyan terrorist group had claimed</i>
<i>responsibility for the alleged theft.</i>

12
00:02:01,607 --> 00:02:06,397
<i>However, officials now attribute</i>
<i>the discrepancy to a simple clerical error.</i>

13
00:02:06,487 --> 00:02:10,002
<i>The FBI, which is investigating the matter,</i>
<i>had no comment.</i>

14
00:02:16,727 --> 00:02:17,716
[Buzzer blares]

15
00:02:50,127 --> 00:02:51,276
MARTY: Doc?

16
00:02:53,887 --> 00:02:54,956
<i>Doc?</i>

17
00:02:56,087 --> 00:02:58,078
<i>Hello! Anybody home?</i>

18
00:02:58,167 --> 00:02:59,441
<i>Einstein, come here, boy.</i>

19
00:02:59,527 --> 00:03:00,642
[Marty whistles]

20
00:03:00,727 --> 00:03:02,558
MARTY: What's going on? God.

21
00:03:04,127 --> 00:03:05,242
<i>Jesus!</i>

22
00:03:05,807 --> 00:03:07,638
<i>That is disgusting.</i>

23
00:03:07,847 --> 00:03:09,360
[Marty muttering]

24
00:03:12,407 --> 00:03:13,999
[Clocks ticking]

25
00:03:15,127 --> 00:03:16,640
[Machine humming]

26
00:03:26,927 --> 00:03:28,599
[Humming grows louder]

27
00:03:31,407 --> 00:03:32,920
[Humming grows very loud]

28
00:03:33,087 --> 00:03:34,725
[Dial clicking]

29
00:04:03,967 --> 00:04:05,605
[Electric guitar note plays]

30
00:04:06,487 --> 00:04:07,761
[Marty grunts]

31
00:04:14,967 --> 00:04:16,844
[Marty groaning]

32
00:04:29,807 --> 00:04:31,240
Rock 'n' roll.

33
00:04:31,367 --> 00:04:33,085
[Alarm bell ringing]

34
00:04:39,047 --> 00:04:40,878
MARTY: Yo.
DOC: <i>Marty, is that you?</i>

35
00:04:41,087 --> 00:04:42,884
Doc. Where are you?

36
00:04:42,967 --> 00:04:46,277
DOC: <i>Thank God I've found you. Meet me</i>
<i>at Twin Pines Mall tonight at 1:15.</i>

37
00:04:46,367 --> 00:04:48,756
<i>I made a breakthrough.</i>
<i>I'll need your assistance.</i>

38
00:04:48,847 --> 00:04:51,964
1:15 in the morning?
Doc, what's going on?

39
00:04:52,047 --> 00:04:53,958
MARTY: Where you been all week?
DOC: <i>Working.</i>

40
00:04:54,047 --> 00:04:57,005
MARTY: Is Einstein with you?
DOC: <i>Yeah, he's right here.</i>

41
00:04:57,087 --> 00:04:59,476
You left your equipment on all week.

42
00:04:59,567 --> 00:05:02,035
DOC: <i>My equipment. That reminds me, Marty.</i>

43
00:05:02,127 --> 00:05:05,881
<i>Do not hook up to the amplifier.</i>
<i>There's a slight possibility of overload.</i>

44
00:05:05,967 --> 00:05:08,162
Yeah. I'll keep that in mind.

45
00:05:08,247 --> 00:05:10,522
DOC: <i>Good. I'll see you tonight. Don't forget.</i>

46
00:05:10,607 --> 00:05:13,405
DOC: <i>1:15 a.m., Twin Pines Mall.</i>
MARTY: Right.

47
00:05:13,527 --> 00:05:16,121
[Clocks all ringing, chiming, cuckooing]

48
00:05:19,807 --> 00:05:24,244
DOC: <i>Are those my clocks I hear?</i>
MARTY: Yeah, it's 8:00.

49
00:05:24,727 --> 00:05:26,718
DOC: <i>Perfect! My experiment worked!</i>

50
00:05:26,807 --> 00:05:29,844
<i>They're all exactly 25 minutes slow!</i>

51
00:05:30,207 --> 00:05:32,562
Wait a minute, Doc.

52
00:05:32,647 --> 00:05:34,842
Are you telling me that it's 8:25?

53
00:05:34,927 --> 00:05:37,077
DOC: <i>Precisely.</i>
MARTY: Damn!

54
00:05:37,967 --> 00:05:39,798
I'm late for school.

55
00:05:39,887 --> 00:05:42,321
[<i>The Power of Love</i> playing]

56
00:06:36,807 --> 00:06:39,526
MARTY: Jennifer.
JENNIFER: Strickland's looking for you.

57
00:06:39,607 --> 00:06:42,167
If you get caught,
it'll be four tardies in a row.

58
00:06:43,767 --> 00:06:45,962
All right, come on. I think we're safe.

59
00:06:46,047 --> 00:06:50,404
This time it wasn't my fault.
The doc set all his clocks 25 minutes slow.

60
00:06:50,487 --> 00:06:51,681
The doc?

61
00:06:51,767 --> 00:06:55,806
Am I to understand you're still hanging
around with Dr. Emmett Brown, McFly?

62
00:06:56,567 --> 00:06:58,558
Tardy slip for you, Miss Parker.

63
00:06:59,167 --> 00:07:02,204
And one for you, McFly.
I believe that's four in a row.

64
00:07:02,727 --> 00:07:05,560
Let me give you a nickel's worth
of free advice, young man.

65
00:07:05,647 --> 00:07:08,684
This so-called Dr. Brown is dangerous.
He's a real nutcase.

66
00:07:08,767 --> 00:07:11,281
Hang around with him,
you'll end up in big trouble.

67
00:07:11,367 --> 00:07:12,880
Yes, sir.

68
00:07:13,087 --> 00:07:16,159
You got a real attitude problem.
You're a slacker.

69
00:07:16,767 --> 00:07:20,555
You remind me of your father
when he went here. He was a slacker, too.

70
00:07:20,807 --> 00:07:22,798
Can I go now, Mr. Strickland?

71
00:07:22,887 --> 00:07:26,357
Your band is on the roster for
the dance auditions after school today.

72
00:07:26,447 --> 00:07:28,756
Why even bother?
You don't have a chance.

73
00:07:28,847 --> 00:07:30,678
You're too much like your old man.

74
00:07:30,767 --> 00:07:34,555
No McFly ever amounted to anything
in the history of Hill Valley.

75
00:07:36,367 --> 00:07:38,597
Yeah, well, history is going to change.

76
00:07:40,647 --> 00:07:42,000
<i>Next, please.</i>

77
00:07:43,087 --> 00:07:44,725
[Synthesizer playing]

78
00:07:50,927 --> 00:07:52,406
<i>All right.</i>

79
00:07:53,007 --> 00:07:55,919
<i>We're the Pinheads.</i>

80
00:07:57,167 --> 00:07:58,600
MARTY: <i>One, two, three.</i>

81
00:07:58,727 --> 00:08:00,718
[Playing <i>Power of Love</i>]

82
00:08:17,407 --> 00:08:20,319
<i>Okay, that's enough. Thank you, fellas.</i>

83
00:08:20,407 --> 00:08:22,443
<i>Hold it, fellas.</i>

84
00:08:22,887 --> 00:08:25,117
<i>I'm afraid you're just too darn loud.</i>

85
00:08:25,847 --> 00:08:27,326
<i>Next, please.</i>

86
00:08:29,407 --> 00:08:31,238
<i>Next group, please.</i>

87
00:08:33,687 --> 00:08:36,326
ANNOUNCER: <i>Re-elect Mayor Goldie Wilson.</i>

88
00:08:36,407 --> 00:08:38,398
<i>Progress is his middle name.</i>

89
00:08:38,487 --> 00:08:40,284
MARTY: <i>"</i>Too loud.<i>"</i> I can't believe it.

90
00:08:40,367 --> 00:08:43,006
We'll never get a chance
to play in front of anybody.

91
00:08:43,087 --> 00:08:45,442
Marty, one rejection
isn't the end of the world.

92
00:08:45,527 --> 00:08:47,757
I just don't think I'm cut out for music.

93
00:08:47,847 --> 00:08:51,317
But you're really good,
and your audition tape is great.

94
00:08:51,407 --> 00:08:53,602
You've got to send it in
to the record company.

95
00:08:53,687 --> 00:08:55,405
- It's like Doc's always saying.
- I know.

96
00:08:55,487 --> 00:08:58,559
If you put your mind to it,
you can accomplish anything.

97
00:08:59,007 --> 00:09:00,759
That's good advice.

98
00:09:00,847 --> 00:09:04,362
All right. What if I send in the tape
and they don't like it?

99
00:09:04,447 --> 00:09:06,278
What if they say I'm no good?

100
00:09:06,367 --> 00:09:08,358
What if they say, <i>"</i>You got no future<i>"</i>?

101
00:09:08,447 --> 00:09:10,722
I can't take that kind of rejection.

102
00:09:11,887 --> 00:09:13,718
I'm starting to sound like my old man.

103
00:09:13,807 --> 00:09:15,718
- He's not that bad.
- Save the clock tower.

104
00:09:15,807 --> 00:09:18,446
He's letting you borrow the car
tomorrow night.

105
00:09:19,607 --> 00:09:21,438
Check out that 4x4.

106
00:09:21,927 --> 00:09:24,487
MARTY: That is hot.
ATTENDANT: Back her up.

107
00:09:24,567 --> 00:09:27,798
Someday, Jennifer. Someday.

108
00:09:28,287 --> 00:09:31,324
Wouldn't it be great
to take that truck up to the lake?

109
00:09:32,607 --> 00:09:35,280
Throw a couple of sleeping bags
in the back.

110
00:09:36,767 --> 00:09:38,644
Lie out underneath the stars.

111
00:09:38,727 --> 00:09:40,479
- Stop it.
- What?

112
00:09:41,287 --> 00:09:43,721
Does your mom know?
About tomorrow night?

113
00:09:43,807 --> 00:09:47,686
No, get out of town. My mom thinks
I'm going camping with the guys.

114
00:09:47,767 --> 00:09:50,645
My mother would freak out
if she knew I was going with you.

115
00:09:50,727 --> 00:09:52,604
I'd get the standard lecture about...

116
00:09:52,687 --> 00:09:55,155
...how she never did that stuff
when she was a kid.

117
00:09:55,247 --> 00:09:57,886
Look, I think the woman was born a nun.

118
00:09:57,967 --> 00:10:00,561
She's just trying to keep you respectable.

119
00:10:00,647 --> 00:10:02,717
She's not doing a very good job.

120
00:10:02,807 --> 00:10:04,001
Terrible.

121
00:10:04,087 --> 00:10:07,557
WOMAN: Save the clock tower.
Save the clock tower.

122
00:10:07,647 --> 00:10:11,526
Mayor Wilson is sponsoring
an initiative to replace that clock.

123
00:10:11,607 --> 00:10:15,839
<i>Thirty years ago, lightning struck that</i>
<i>clock tower and the clock hasn't run since.</i>

124
00:10:15,927 --> 00:10:20,523
We at the Hill Valley Preservation Society
think it should be preserved the way it is...

125
00:10:20,607 --> 00:10:22,643
<i>... as part of our history and heritage.</i>

126
00:10:22,727 --> 00:10:24,479
MARTY: There's a quarter.
WOMAN: Thanks.

127
00:10:24,567 --> 00:10:26,398
WOMAN: Don't forget to take a flyer.

128
00:10:26,487 --> 00:10:28,318
<i>Save the clock tower!</i>

129
00:10:30,087 --> 00:10:31,076
Where were we?

130
00:10:31,207 --> 00:10:32,196
[Car horn honks]

131
00:10:32,287 --> 00:10:34,437
JENNIFER: Right about here.
MAN: Jennifer!

132
00:10:37,207 --> 00:10:39,482
It's my dad. I've got to go.

133
00:10:39,567 --> 00:10:40,795
MARTY: I'll call you tonight.

134
00:10:40,887 --> 00:10:42,115
I'll be at my grandma's.

135
00:10:42,207 --> 00:10:44,516
Here, let me give you the number.

136
00:10:49,327 --> 00:10:50,282
'Bye.

137
00:10:50,367 --> 00:10:52,597
[<i>Power of Love</i> music playing]

138
00:11:22,247 --> 00:11:23,600
[Dog barking]

139
00:11:31,767 --> 00:11:34,645
RADIO DISPATCHER:
<i>Bravo, Tango, Delta 6-2-9.</i>

140
00:11:34,727 --> 00:11:37,366
<i>Tow for impoundment.</i>
<i>Any unit, please respond.</i>

141
00:11:40,007 --> 00:11:42,396
MARTY: Perfect. Just perfect.

142
00:11:46,447 --> 00:11:48,199
[Biff speaking muffled]

143
00:11:48,687 --> 00:11:50,723
BIFF: I can't believe you'd loan me your car...

144
00:11:50,807 --> 00:11:52,877
...without telling me it had a blind spot.

145
00:11:52,967 --> 00:11:54,480
I could've been killed.

146
00:11:54,567 --> 00:11:56,956
Now, Biff, I never noticed...

147
00:11:57,047 --> 00:12:00,722
...that the car had any blind spot before
when I would drive it.

148
00:12:00,807 --> 00:12:02,160
Hi, son.

149
00:12:02,247 --> 00:12:03,965
BIFF: Are you blind, McFly?

150
00:12:04,047 --> 00:12:06,242
<i>How else do you explain</i>
<i>that wreck out there?</i>

151
00:12:06,327 --> 00:12:09,444
MR. MCFLY: Biff, can I assume...

152
00:12:09,607 --> 00:12:12,485
...that your insurance
is going to pay for the damage?

153
00:12:12,567 --> 00:12:14,797
My insurance? It's your car.

154
00:12:14,887 --> 00:12:17,685
Your insurance should pay.
Who's going to pay for this?

155
00:12:17,767 --> 00:12:21,646
I spilled beer when the car smashed
into me. Who'll pay my cleaning bill?

156
00:12:21,727 --> 00:12:23,558
<i>And where's my reports?</i>

157
00:12:23,647 --> 00:12:27,765
I haven't finished those up yet,
but I figured since they weren't due 'til...

158
00:12:27,847 --> 00:12:30,645
Hello? Hello? Anybody home?

159
00:12:31,327 --> 00:12:33,682
Think, McFly. Think!

160
00:12:33,767 --> 00:12:35,598
I got to have time to get them retyped.

161
00:12:35,687 --> 00:12:39,726
Do you realize what would happen
if I hand in my reports in your handwriting?

162
00:12:39,807 --> 00:12:41,320
I'll get fired.

163
00:12:41,407 --> 00:12:43,967
You wouldn't want that to happen,
would you?

164
00:12:44,047 --> 00:12:45,924
- Would you?
- Of course not.

165
00:12:46,007 --> 00:12:48,396
I wouldn't want that to happen.

166
00:12:48,487 --> 00:12:50,842
<i>Now, look.</i>
<i>I'll finish those reports tonight...</i>

167
00:12:50,927 --> 00:12:54,044
...and I'll run them on over
first thing tomorrow.

168
00:12:54,127 --> 00:12:56,083
Not too early. I sleep in Saturday.

169
00:12:56,167 --> 00:12:57,998
Your shoe's untied.

170
00:12:58,287 --> 00:13:00,596
Don't be so gullible, McFly.

171
00:13:00,687 --> 00:13:02,518
<i>Got the place fixed up nice.</i>

172
00:13:04,527 --> 00:13:06,563
I have your car towed to your house...

173
00:13:06,647 --> 00:13:08,956
...and all you got for me is lite beer?

174
00:13:15,807 --> 00:13:17,877
What are you looking at, butthead?

175
00:13:20,087 --> 00:13:21,918
Say hi to your mom for me.

176
00:13:24,727 --> 00:13:26,718
I know what you're going to say, son...

177
00:13:26,807 --> 00:13:28,399
...and you're right.

178
00:13:28,487 --> 00:13:29,806
You're right.

179
00:13:30,367 --> 00:13:31,356
But...

180
00:13:32,087 --> 00:13:34,043
Biff just happens to be my supervisor...

181
00:13:34,127 --> 00:13:38,757
...and I'm afraid I'm just not
very good at confrontations.

182
00:13:39,687 --> 00:13:41,405
But the car, Dad.

183
00:13:41,487 --> 00:13:42,920
[Car driving away]

184
00:13:43,127 --> 00:13:45,402
MARTY: I mean, he wrecked it.
He totaled it.

185
00:13:46,567 --> 00:13:48,558
I needed that car tomorrow night, Dad.

186
00:13:48,647 --> 00:13:51,798
Do you have any idea
how important this was to me?

187
00:13:51,887 --> 00:13:54,321
MR. MCFLY: I know, and all I can say is, I'm...

188
00:13:54,967 --> 00:13:56,366
I'm sorry.

189
00:13:56,647 --> 00:13:58,717
MR. MCFLY: Believe me, Marty, you're better off...

190
00:13:58,807 --> 00:14:01,799
...without having to worry
about all the aggravation...

191
00:14:01,887 --> 00:14:05,004
...and headaches of playing at that dance.

192
00:14:05,087 --> 00:14:08,841
DAVID: He's absolutely right.
The last thing you need is headaches.

193
00:14:09,927 --> 00:14:11,645
[Mr. McFly laughing]

194
00:14:11,767 --> 00:14:13,405
[David laughing]

195
00:14:15,127 --> 00:14:16,606
[TV audience applauding]

196
00:14:16,687 --> 00:14:20,157
Kids, we're going to have to
eat this cake by ourselves.

197
00:14:20,727 --> 00:14:23,002
Your Uncle Joey didn't make parole again.

198
00:14:23,967 --> 00:14:25,195
[Mrs. McFly sighs]

199
00:14:25,287 --> 00:14:28,404
It would be nice
if you all dropped him a line.

200
00:14:28,567 --> 00:14:30,159
MARTY: Uncle <i>"</i>Jailbird<i>"</i> Joey?

201
00:14:30,247 --> 00:14:31,726
He's your brother, Mom.

202
00:14:31,807 --> 00:14:35,402
Yeah. It's a major embarrassment,
having an uncle in prison.

203
00:14:35,647 --> 00:14:37,683
We all make mistakes in life, children.

204
00:14:37,767 --> 00:14:39,405
DAVID: Goddamn it. I'm late.

205
00:14:39,487 --> 00:14:41,079
MRS. MCFLY: David, watch your mouth!

206
00:14:41,167 --> 00:14:43,635
You come here and kiss your mother
before you go.

207
00:14:43,727 --> 00:14:46,685
Come on, Mom.
Make it fast. I'll miss my bus.

208
00:14:47,127 --> 00:14:48,242
DAVID: See you later, Pop.

209
00:14:48,367 --> 00:14:49,356
[David exclaims]

210
00:14:49,447 --> 00:14:51,244
Time to change that oil.

211
00:14:51,447 --> 00:14:52,641
[Laughing]

212
00:14:54,287 --> 00:14:55,242
LINDA: Marty.

213
00:14:55,967 --> 00:14:57,685
I'm not your answering service.

214
00:14:57,767 --> 00:15:00,076
While you were outside
pouting over the car...

215
00:15:00,167 --> 00:15:02,044
...Jennifer Parker called you twice.

216
00:15:02,127 --> 00:15:03,606
MRS. MCFLY: I don't like her.

217
00:15:03,687 --> 00:15:06,838
Any girl who calls up a boy
is just asking for trouble.

218
00:15:06,927 --> 00:15:09,680
LINDA: Mom. There's nothing wrong
with calling a boy.

219
00:15:09,767 --> 00:15:13,442
I think it's terrible. Girls chasing boys.

220
00:15:13,527 --> 00:15:16,724
When I was your age,
I never chased a boy or called a boy or...

221
00:15:16,807 --> 00:15:19,241
...sat in a parked car with a boy.

222
00:15:19,887 --> 00:15:22,401
LINDA: Then how am I ever
supposed to meet anybody?

223
00:15:23,287 --> 00:15:25,482
Well, it'll just happen.

224
00:15:25,687 --> 00:15:27,917
Like the way I met your father.

225
00:15:28,007 --> 00:15:30,999
That was so stupid.
Grandpa hit him with the car.

226
00:15:31,287 --> 00:15:32,686
It was meant to be.

227
00:15:32,807 --> 00:15:33,796
[Linda sighs]

228
00:15:33,887 --> 00:15:35,161
Anyway...

229
00:15:35,567 --> 00:15:38,843
...if Grandpa hadn't hit him,
then none of you would have been born.

230
00:15:38,927 --> 00:15:40,440
Yeah, well.

231
00:15:40,527 --> 00:15:43,837
I don't understand what Dad was doing
in the middle of the street.

232
00:15:43,927 --> 00:15:46,282
MRS. MCFLY:
What was it, George? Bird-watching?

233
00:15:46,367 --> 00:15:48,801
What, Lorraine? What?

234
00:15:48,887 --> 00:15:51,685
Anyway, your Grandpa
hit him with the car...

235
00:15:51,767 --> 00:15:53,837
...and brought him into the house.

236
00:15:54,727 --> 00:15:56,558
He seemed so helpless.

237
00:15:59,207 --> 00:16:02,085
Like a little lost puppy,
and my heart just went out to him.

238
00:16:02,167 --> 00:16:05,204
LINDA: Yeah, we know.
You've told us this story a million times.

239
00:16:05,287 --> 00:16:06,640
<i>You felt sorry for him.</i>

240
00:16:06,727 --> 00:16:09,685
You decided to go with him
to the Fish Under the Sea dance.

241
00:16:09,767 --> 00:16:12,679
No. It was
the Enchantment Under the Sea dance.

242
00:16:13,527 --> 00:16:16,519
Our first date. I'll never forget it.

243
00:16:16,967 --> 00:16:20,482
It was the night of that terrible
thunderstorm, remember, George?

244
00:16:20,567 --> 00:16:22,364
[Lndistinct chatter on TV]

245
00:16:23,047 --> 00:16:26,517
Your father kissed me
for the first time on that dance floor.

246
00:16:28,647 --> 00:16:30,683
It was then that I realized...

247
00:16:30,807 --> 00:16:33,844
...that I was going to spend
the rest of my life with him.

248
00:16:33,967 --> 00:16:35,798
[Mr. McFly laughing]

249
00:16:37,367 --> 00:16:38,686
Oh, no.

250
00:16:44,007 --> 00:16:45,565
[Music playing on radio]

251
00:16:55,167 --> 00:16:56,646
[Telephone ringing]

252
00:17:00,087 --> 00:17:01,236
[Sighing]

253
00:17:01,407 --> 00:17:02,476
Hello.

254
00:17:02,567 --> 00:17:05,161
DOC: <i>Marty, you didn't fall asleep, did you?</i>
MARTY: Doc.

255
00:17:06,367 --> 00:17:08,961
No. No, don't be silly.

256
00:17:09,127 --> 00:17:11,880
DOC: <i>Listen, this is very important.</i>
<i>I forgot my video camera.</i>

257
00:17:11,967 --> 00:17:14,686
<i>Can you pick it up at my place</i>
<i>on your way to the mall?</i>

258
00:17:14,767 --> 00:17:17,327
Yeah. I'm on my way.

259
00:17:40,607 --> 00:17:43,519
Einstein! Where's the doc, boy?

260
00:17:43,607 --> 00:17:44,926
[Einstein whining]

261
00:17:45,007 --> 00:17:46,440
[Machine humming]

262
00:17:49,327 --> 00:17:50,680
[Gate unlocking]

263
00:17:56,487 --> 00:17:58,284
[Mysterious instrumental music]

264
00:18:08,207 --> 00:18:09,322
[Engine revving]

265
00:18:09,407 --> 00:18:11,204
[Dramatic instrumental music]

266
00:18:31,407 --> 00:18:32,886
[Steam rushing]

267
00:18:35,607 --> 00:18:36,676
Doc!

268
00:18:37,927 --> 00:18:40,077
- Marty! You made it!
- Yeah.

269
00:18:40,367 --> 00:18:44,565
Welcome to my latest experiment. This is
the one I've been waiting for all my life.

270
00:18:44,647 --> 00:18:46,160
Well, it's a DeLorean...

271
00:18:46,247 --> 00:18:50,001
All your questions will be answered.
Roll tape and we'll proceed.

272
00:18:50,087 --> 00:18:52,362
- Is that a Devo suit?
- Never mind that now.

273
00:18:52,447 --> 00:18:54,563
DOC: Not now.
MARTY: I'm ready.

274
00:18:55,167 --> 00:18:58,955
Good evening. I'm Dr. Emmett Brown.
I'm in the Twin Pines Mall parking lot.

275
00:18:59,047 --> 00:19:02,483
It's Saturday morning,
October 26, 1985, 1:18 a.m.

276
00:19:02,567 --> 00:19:04,717
<i>This is temporal experiment number one.</i>

277
00:19:04,807 --> 00:19:07,640
DOC: Come on, Einie. Get in there.

278
00:19:07,807 --> 00:19:09,684
In you go. Sit down.

279
00:19:09,967 --> 00:19:11,958
Put your seat belt on.

280
00:19:13,407 --> 00:19:15,079
[Einstein grunting]

281
00:19:17,407 --> 00:19:18,726
MARTY: Okay.

282
00:19:20,007 --> 00:19:22,521
Please note that Einstein's clock...

283
00:19:22,607 --> 00:19:25,440
...is in precise synchronization
with my control watch.

284
00:19:25,527 --> 00:19:27,643
DOC: Got it?
MARTY: Right. Check, Doc.

285
00:19:30,127 --> 00:19:33,085
DOC: Have a good trip, Einstein.
Watch your head.

286
00:19:38,407 --> 00:19:40,967
MARTY:
You got that thing hooked up to the car?

287
00:19:41,047 --> 00:19:42,958
DOC: Watch this.
MARTY: Yeah. Okay.

288
00:19:43,047 --> 00:19:44,400
MARTY: Got it.

289
00:19:48,087 --> 00:19:49,156
Jesus!

290
00:19:53,887 --> 00:19:55,445
Not me! The car!

291
00:19:57,327 --> 00:19:58,965
[Tires squealing]

292
00:20:05,407 --> 00:20:06,886
[Engine revving]

293
00:20:12,127 --> 00:20:14,482
If my calculations are correct...

294
00:20:14,847 --> 00:20:17,361
...when this baby hits 88 miles per hour...

295
00:20:17,807 --> 00:20:20,082
...you're going to see some serious shit.

296
00:20:22,207 --> 00:20:23,196
[Remote control beeping]

297
00:20:23,487 --> 00:20:25,045
[Tires squealing]

298
00:20:25,527 --> 00:20:26,880
[Remote control beeping]

299
00:20:26,967 --> 00:20:28,161
[Tires squealing]

300
00:20:28,407 --> 00:20:29,362
[Remote control beeping]

301
00:20:29,447 --> 00:20:31,199
[Tires squealing]

302
00:20:54,287 --> 00:20:55,925
Watch this!

303
00:20:58,007 --> 00:20:58,996
[Beeping growing faster]

304
00:21:09,327 --> 00:21:11,522
[Dramatic instrumental music]

305
00:21:12,207 --> 00:21:13,196
[Doc laughs]

306
00:21:13,287 --> 00:21:15,517
What did I tell you?

307
00:21:15,607 --> 00:21:18,917
88 miles per hour!

308
00:21:21,887 --> 00:21:26,597
The temporal displacement occurred
exactly 1:20 a.m. And zero seconds!

309
00:21:28,287 --> 00:21:30,039
Jesus Christ!

310
00:21:30,127 --> 00:21:32,482
Jesus Christ, Doc!
You disintegrated Einstein!

311
00:21:32,567 --> 00:21:35,035
Calm down. I didn't disintegrate anything.

312
00:21:35,167 --> 00:21:39,206
The molecular structure of both Einstein
and the car are completely intact.

313
00:21:39,767 --> 00:21:41,086
Then where the hell are they?

314
00:21:41,167 --> 00:21:44,159
The appropriate question is,
<i>"</i>When the hell are they?<i>"</i>

315
00:21:44,247 --> 00:21:48,525
Einstein has just become
the world's first time traveler.

316
00:21:49,007 --> 00:21:51,521
DOC: I sent him into the future.

317
00:21:52,527 --> 00:21:54,802
One minute into the future, to be exact.

318
00:21:54,887 --> 00:21:57,959
At precisely 1:21 a.m. And zero seconds...

319
00:21:58,047 --> 00:22:00,925
...we shall catch up with him
and the time machine.

320
00:22:02,607 --> 00:22:03,722
[Dramatic instrumental music ends]

321
00:22:04,207 --> 00:22:06,118
Wait a minute, Doc.

322
00:22:07,727 --> 00:22:10,605
Are you telling me that
you built a time machine...

323
00:22:11,647 --> 00:22:13,797
...out of a DeLorean?
- The way I see it...

324
00:22:13,887 --> 00:22:17,766
...if you're going to build a time machine
into a car, why not do it with style?

325
00:22:17,847 --> 00:22:20,998
Besides, the stainless-steel construction
made the flux dispersal...

326
00:22:21,127 --> 00:22:22,116
[Watch beeping]

327
00:22:22,207 --> 00:22:23,560
Look out!

328
00:22:25,087 --> 00:22:26,725
[Tires squealing]

329
00:22:28,647 --> 00:22:30,205
[Remote control beeps]

330
00:23:02,567 --> 00:23:04,444
[Time machine steaming and creaking]

331
00:23:05,167 --> 00:23:06,361
[Doc gasps]

332
00:23:06,607 --> 00:23:09,405
MARTY: What? Is it hot?
DOC: It's cold. Damn cold.

333
00:23:11,687 --> 00:23:12,836
[Doc laughing]

334
00:23:12,967 --> 00:23:15,117
Einstein, you little devil!

335
00:23:17,207 --> 00:23:20,916
<i>Einstein's clock is exactly one minute</i>
<i>behind mine and still ticking!</i>

336
00:23:24,287 --> 00:23:25,800
MARTY: He's okay.
DOC: He's fine.

337
00:23:25,887 --> 00:23:28,082
He's completely unaware
that anything happened.

338
00:23:28,167 --> 00:23:30,727
As far as he's concerned,
the trip was instantaneous.

339
00:23:30,807 --> 00:23:33,321
That's why his watch is exactly
one minute behind mine.

340
00:23:33,407 --> 00:23:37,036
He skipped over that minute to
instantly arrive at this moment in time.

341
00:23:37,127 --> 00:23:39,402
I'll show you how it works.

342
00:23:40,887 --> 00:23:43,799
First, you turn the time circuits on.

343
00:23:43,887 --> 00:23:45,036
[Machine powering up]

344
00:23:45,927 --> 00:23:47,246
[Machine whirs]

345
00:23:47,407 --> 00:23:51,286
DOC: This tells you where you're going,
this where you are and this where you were.

346
00:23:51,367 --> 00:23:53,756
Input your destination time on this keypad.

347
00:23:53,847 --> 00:23:57,317
Say you want to see the signing
of the Declaration of Independence.

348
00:23:57,687 --> 00:23:58,836
[Machine bleeps]

349
00:23:59,287 --> 00:24:01,243
DOC: Or witness the birth of Christ.

350
00:24:04,127 --> 00:24:06,721
Here's a red-letter date
in the history of science.

351
00:24:06,807 --> 00:24:09,446
November 5, 1955.

352
00:24:13,047 --> 00:24:14,480
Yes, of course.

353
00:24:14,567 --> 00:24:17,400
November 5, 1955.

354
00:24:18,047 --> 00:24:19,765
What happened?

355
00:24:20,807 --> 00:24:23,116
That was the day I invented time travel.

356
00:24:23,487 --> 00:24:24,966
<i>I remember it vividly.</i>

357
00:24:25,047 --> 00:24:27,003
I was standing on my toilet
hanging a clock.

358
00:24:27,087 --> 00:24:29,806
The porcelain was wet.
I slipped, hit my head on the sink.

359
00:24:29,887 --> 00:24:31,718
When I came to, I had a revelation.

360
00:24:31,807 --> 00:24:35,356
A vision. A picture in my head.
A picture of this.

361
00:24:35,807 --> 00:24:38,367
<i>This is what makes time travel possible.</i>

362
00:24:38,887 --> 00:24:40,605
The flux capacitor.

363
00:24:40,887 --> 00:24:42,036
Flux capacitor?

364
00:24:42,127 --> 00:24:46,564
It's taken almost 30 years and my family
fortune to realize the vision of that day.

365
00:24:46,967 --> 00:24:49,117
My God, has it been that long?

366
00:24:49,767 --> 00:24:52,201
Things have certainly changed around here.

367
00:24:53,407 --> 00:24:57,082
I remember when this was all farmland
as far as the eye could see.

368
00:24:58,527 --> 00:25:00,882
Old man Peabody owned all of this.

369
00:25:02,087 --> 00:25:05,841
He had this crazy idea
about breeding pine trees.

370
00:25:09,487 --> 00:25:12,797
This is...
This is heavy-duty, Doc. This is great.

371
00:25:13,247 --> 00:25:15,715
Does it run on regular unleaded gasoline?

372
00:25:15,807 --> 00:25:19,482
Unfortunately, no. It requires something
with a little more kick. Plutonium.

373
00:25:19,567 --> 00:25:21,717
Plutonium. Wait a minute.

374
00:25:21,807 --> 00:25:24,446
Are you telling me
that this sucker is nuclear?

375
00:25:24,647 --> 00:25:26,000
Keep rolling there.

376
00:25:26,087 --> 00:25:27,839
No, this sucker's electrical...

377
00:25:27,927 --> 00:25:31,966
...but I need a nuclear reaction to generate
the 1.21 gigawatts of electricity I need.

378
00:25:32,047 --> 00:25:35,198
You don't just walk into a store
and buy plutonium.

379
00:25:35,607 --> 00:25:37,518
<i>Did you rip that off?</i>

380
00:25:39,247 --> 00:25:43,001
Of course. From a group of Libyans.
They wanted me to build them a bomb.

381
00:25:43,087 --> 00:25:47,319
I took the plutonium and gave them a
bomb casing full of pinball machine parts.

382
00:25:47,407 --> 00:25:50,205
DOC: Come on. Let's get you a radiation suit.
MARTY: Jesus!

383
00:25:57,127 --> 00:25:59,118
[Breathing distorted by suit]

384
00:26:12,567 --> 00:26:13,920
[Sucking]

385
00:26:18,647 --> 00:26:21,036
It's safe now. Everything's lead-lined.

386
00:26:21,127 --> 00:26:22,685
[Suspenseful instrumental music]

387
00:26:22,767 --> 00:26:24,644
DOC: Don't lose those tapes now.

388
00:26:24,727 --> 00:26:26,604
I need that as a record.

389
00:26:26,687 --> 00:26:28,917
Let's put this back here. There we go.

390
00:26:31,247 --> 00:26:32,919
Almost forgot my luggage.

391
00:26:33,047 --> 00:26:35,686
Who knows if they got
cotton underwear in the future.

392
00:26:35,767 --> 00:26:38,645
- I'm allergic to all synthetics.
- The future.

393
00:26:38,887 --> 00:26:40,639
- That's where you're going.
- Right.

394
00:26:40,727 --> 00:26:44,925
25 years. I've always dreamed of seeing
the future, looking beyond my years...

395
00:26:45,007 --> 00:26:47,077
...seeing the progress of mankind.

396
00:26:47,167 --> 00:26:48,282
MARTY: Why not?

397
00:26:48,367 --> 00:26:51,643
I'll also be able to see
who wins the next 25 World Series.

398
00:26:52,367 --> 00:26:53,322
MARTY: Doc.

399
00:26:54,687 --> 00:26:56,996
Look me up when you get there.

400
00:26:57,687 --> 00:27:00,121
Indeed I will. Roll 'em.

401
00:27:03,007 --> 00:27:04,326
[Doc clearing throat]

402
00:27:06,207 --> 00:27:08,926
I, Dr. Emmett Brown...

403
00:27:10,087 --> 00:27:12,647
...am about to embark
on an historic journey.

404
00:27:14,687 --> 00:27:16,484
What am I thinking of?

405
00:27:16,567 --> 00:27:18,637
I almost forgot to bring extra plutonium.

406
00:27:18,727 --> 00:27:21,161
How do I expect to get back?
One pellet, one trip.

407
00:27:21,247 --> 00:27:23,238
I must be out of my mind.

408
00:27:23,327 --> 00:27:24,840
[Einstein barking]

409
00:27:25,647 --> 00:27:27,205
What is it?

410
00:27:31,407 --> 00:27:33,363
[Ominous instrumental music]

411
00:27:35,367 --> 00:27:36,436
My God.

412
00:27:36,927 --> 00:27:39,600
They found me.
I don't know how, but they found me.

413
00:27:39,687 --> 00:27:41,803
DOC: Run for it, Marty!
MARTY: Who?

414
00:27:42,247 --> 00:27:44,397
Who do you think? The Libyans!

415
00:27:46,127 --> 00:27:47,640
[Man shouting in Arabic]

416
00:27:47,727 --> 00:27:49,206
Holy shit!

417
00:27:49,447 --> 00:27:50,766
[Gunshots firing]

418
00:27:53,047 --> 00:27:54,639
I'll draw their fire!

419
00:28:02,447 --> 00:28:03,766
Doc, wait!

420
00:28:14,767 --> 00:28:16,439
[Doc screaming]

421
00:28:17,447 --> 00:28:18,675
No!

422
00:28:19,527 --> 00:28:21,279
Bastards!

423
00:28:25,807 --> 00:28:27,286
[Shouting in Arabic]

424
00:28:31,327 --> 00:28:32,555
[Grunting]

425
00:28:32,647 --> 00:28:33,762
[Gun clicking]

426
00:28:33,927 --> 00:28:35,519
[Swearing in Arabic]

427
00:28:37,207 --> 00:28:38,322
[Grunting]

428
00:28:39,247 --> 00:28:40,396
Go!

429
00:28:40,487 --> 00:28:41,966
[Engine stalling]

430
00:28:46,247 --> 00:28:47,521
Go!

431
00:28:47,647 --> 00:28:49,000
[Tires squealing]

432
00:28:50,007 --> 00:28:51,440
[Engine starting]

433
00:28:52,647 --> 00:28:54,080
[Tires squealing]

434
00:28:59,967 --> 00:29:01,320
[Machine beeping]

435
00:29:07,247 --> 00:29:08,760
[Gunshots firing and ricocheting]

436
00:29:20,407 --> 00:29:21,556
[Shouting]

437
00:29:26,287 --> 00:29:28,517
Come on! Move! Goddamn it!

438
00:29:30,047 --> 00:29:31,321
MARTY: Jesus!

439
00:29:39,727 --> 00:29:41,604
[Dramatic instrumental music]

440
00:29:50,647 --> 00:29:52,046
Holy shit!

441
00:29:52,767 --> 00:29:55,486
Let's see if you bastards can do 90.

442
00:29:55,647 --> 00:29:56,921
[Tires squealing]

443
00:30:12,727 --> 00:30:14,080
[Rumbling over ground]

444
00:30:15,207 --> 00:30:16,435
[Screaming]

445
00:30:21,127 --> 00:30:22,560
[Crashing]

446
00:30:25,087 --> 00:30:26,566
[Chickens clucking]

447
00:30:27,167 --> 00:30:28,520
[Crickets chirping]

448
00:30:28,847 --> 00:30:30,166
[Dog barking distantly]

449
00:30:30,967 --> 00:30:32,195
[Door creaks open]

450
00:30:38,767 --> 00:30:40,200
[Car blinker clicking]

451
00:30:45,047 --> 00:30:46,366
WOMAN: Pa, what is it?

452
00:30:46,527 --> 00:30:47,926
What is it, Pa?

453
00:30:48,007 --> 00:30:51,158
Looks like an airplane without wings.

454
00:30:51,687 --> 00:30:54,679
That ain't no airplane. Look.

455
00:30:59,447 --> 00:31:00,880
[Hydraulics hissing]

456
00:31:08,567 --> 00:31:10,319
[Muffled breathing]

457
00:31:11,327 --> 00:31:12,680
[Screaming]

458
00:31:14,607 --> 00:31:15,926
Don't look!

459
00:31:16,007 --> 00:31:17,599
MARTY: Listen...

460
00:31:20,407 --> 00:31:22,045
[Cows mooing]

461
00:31:29,327 --> 00:31:30,476
Hello.

462
00:31:33,487 --> 00:31:34,715
Excuse me.

463
00:31:38,087 --> 00:31:39,679
Sorry about your barn.

464
00:31:39,767 --> 00:31:40,995
[Gunshot fires]

465
00:31:42,887 --> 00:31:46,038
It's already mutated into human form!
Shoot it!

466
00:31:47,887 --> 00:31:50,162
Take that, you mutated son of a bitch!

467
00:31:51,647 --> 00:31:52,875
[Screaming]

468
00:31:54,367 --> 00:31:55,720
BOY: Wait!

469
00:31:57,887 --> 00:31:59,400
BOY: Shoot it, Pa!

470
00:32:01,727 --> 00:32:04,639
MAN: My pine! Why you...

471
00:32:04,727 --> 00:32:05,921
[Gunshot fires]

472
00:32:06,607 --> 00:32:09,883
MAN: You space bastard! You killed my pine!

473
00:32:10,287 --> 00:32:12,278
[Dramatic instrumental music]

474
00:32:13,007 --> 00:32:13,996
[Tires squealing]

475
00:32:14,087 --> 00:32:15,884
MARTY: Okay, McFly.

476
00:32:15,967 --> 00:32:18,083
Get a grip on yourself. It's all a dream.

477
00:32:18,167 --> 00:32:20,886
Just a very intense dream.

478
00:32:23,607 --> 00:32:25,245
[Brakes squealing]

479
00:32:33,647 --> 00:32:35,638
[Mysterious instrumental music]

480
00:32:43,847 --> 00:32:45,758
[Somber instrumental music]

481
00:33:02,127 --> 00:33:05,199
MARTY: Listen, you got to help me.
WOMAN: Don't stop, Wilbur!

482
00:33:07,767 --> 00:33:09,086
It can't be.

483
00:33:11,567 --> 00:33:12,886
[Machine beeps]

484
00:33:14,887 --> 00:33:16,445
This is nuts.

485
00:33:17,247 --> 00:33:18,566
[Engine stalling]

486
00:33:19,207 --> 00:33:20,276
[Engine stalling]

487
00:33:20,407 --> 00:33:21,920
Come on.

488
00:33:22,607 --> 00:33:24,086
Perfect.

489
00:33:24,167 --> 00:33:26,601
[Machine beeping insistently]

490
00:33:53,087 --> 00:33:55,078
[<i>Mr. Sandman</i> playing]

491
00:34:13,687 --> 00:34:15,120
[Car honking]

492
00:34:24,767 --> 00:34:25,756
[Bell dings]

493
00:34:26,727 --> 00:34:28,285
[Gas attendants speaking]

494
00:34:33,127 --> 00:34:34,480
[<i>Mr. Sandman</i> continuing]

495
00:34:43,047 --> 00:34:44,799
[Boy counting]

496
00:34:57,287 --> 00:34:58,959
[Bell chiming]

497
00:35:14,167 --> 00:35:17,921
ANNOUNCER: <i>Remember,</i>
<i>fellow citizens, the future is in your hands.</i>

498
00:35:18,007 --> 00:35:21,522
<i>If you believe in progress,</i>
<i>re-elect Mayor Red Thomas.</i>

499
00:35:21,727 --> 00:35:23,718
<i>Progress is his middle name.</i>

500
00:35:23,807 --> 00:35:26,275
<i>Mayor Red Thomas' progress platform...</i>

501
00:35:26,367 --> 00:35:28,756
<i>... means more jobs, better education...</i>

502
00:35:28,847 --> 00:35:31,805
<i>... bigger civic improvements</i>
<i>and lower taxes.</i>

503
00:35:31,887 --> 00:35:35,436
<i>On election day,</i>
<i>cast your vote for a proven leader.</i>

504
00:35:35,527 --> 00:35:37,722
<i>Re-elect Mayor Red Thomas.</i>

505
00:35:40,927 --> 00:35:42,804
MARTY: This has got to be a dream.

506
00:35:51,767 --> 00:35:53,723
[<i>Davy Crockett</i> playing on jukebox]

507
00:35:59,127 --> 00:36:01,163
MAN: Hey, kid. You jump ship?

508
00:36:02,047 --> 00:36:04,402
- What?
- What's with the life preserver?

509
00:36:09,447 --> 00:36:11,005
I want to use the phone.

510
00:36:11,687 --> 00:36:13,120
It's in the back.

511
00:36:15,687 --> 00:36:16,961
MARTY: Brown.

512
00:36:18,927 --> 00:36:20,360
Great. You're alive.

513
00:36:23,927 --> 00:36:25,440
[Watch beeping]

514
00:36:26,007 --> 00:36:27,122
[Marty sighs]

515
00:36:28,087 --> 00:36:29,520
[Phone ringing]

516
00:36:32,087 --> 00:36:33,440
Come on.

517
00:36:40,487 --> 00:36:44,366
MARTY: Do you know where 1640 Riverside...
MAN: Are you going to order, kid?

518
00:36:46,247 --> 00:36:47,396
Yeah.

519
00:36:47,687 --> 00:36:49,279
<i>Give me a Tab.</i>

520
00:36:49,527 --> 00:36:51,916
I can't give you a tab
unless you order something.

521
00:36:52,007 --> 00:36:53,918
Right. Give me a Pepsi Free.

522
00:36:54,007 --> 00:36:56,601
MAN: You want a Pepsi, pal,
you're going to pay for it.

523
00:36:56,727 --> 00:36:59,685
Just give me something
without any sugar in it, okay?

524
00:36:59,887 --> 00:37:01,639
Something without sugar.

525
00:37:07,727 --> 00:37:09,126
[Door opens]

526
00:37:09,207 --> 00:37:10,322
BIFF: McFly.

527
00:37:12,607 --> 00:37:14,199
What are you doing?

528
00:37:15,087 --> 00:37:16,122
Biff.

529
00:37:16,367 --> 00:37:18,756
I'm talking to you, McFly, you Irish bug!

530
00:37:18,847 --> 00:37:22,601
GEORGE: Biff. Guys. How are you doing?
BIFF: You got my homework finished?

531
00:37:23,287 --> 00:37:25,881
Actually, I figured
since it wasn't due 'til Monday...

532
00:37:25,967 --> 00:37:28,686
Hello? Hello? Anybody home?

533
00:37:29,207 --> 00:37:31,004
Think, McFly. Think!

534
00:37:31,087 --> 00:37:32,884
I got to have time to recopy it.

535
00:37:32,967 --> 00:37:36,562
You realize what would happen if I hand in
my homework in your handwriting?

536
00:37:36,647 --> 00:37:38,319
I'll get kicked out of school.

537
00:37:38,407 --> 00:37:40,875
You wouldn't want that to happen,
would you?

538
00:37:42,927 --> 00:37:44,599
- Would you?
- Of course not.

539
00:37:44,687 --> 00:37:46,518
- No.
- I wouldn't want that to happen.

540
00:37:46,607 --> 00:37:50,395
- What are you looking at, butthead?
- Get a load of his life preserver.

541
00:37:50,487 --> 00:37:52,125
Dork thinks he's going to drown.

542
00:37:52,207 --> 00:37:54,038
BIFF: How about my homework, McFly?

543
00:37:55,087 --> 00:37:56,679
Okay, Biff.

544
00:37:56,807 --> 00:38:01,323
I'll finish that up tonight and then I'll
bring it over first thing tomorrow morning.

545
00:38:01,567 --> 00:38:04,957
Not too early. I sleep in Sundays.
Your shoe's untied!

546
00:38:05,527 --> 00:38:07,483
Don't be so gullible, McFly.

547
00:38:07,567 --> 00:38:11,162
- I don't want to see you in here again.
- Okay. All right. Bye-bye.

548
00:38:32,207 --> 00:38:34,641
- What?
- You're George McFly!

549
00:38:35,007 --> 00:38:36,838
Yeah. Who are you?

550
00:38:36,927 --> 00:38:39,487
Why do you let those boys
push you around like that for?

551
00:38:39,567 --> 00:38:40,886
They're bigger than me.

552
00:38:40,967 --> 00:38:43,197
Stand tall. Have some respect for yourself.

553
00:38:43,327 --> 00:38:47,684
If you let people walk over you now,
they'll walk over you the rest of your life.

554
00:38:47,767 --> 00:38:50,804
Look at me. You think
I'll spend my life in this slop house?

555
00:38:50,887 --> 00:38:52,605
MAN: Watch it, Goldie.
GOLDIE: No, sir!

556
00:38:52,687 --> 00:38:55,076
GOLDIE: I'll do something.
I'll go to night school.

557
00:38:55,167 --> 00:38:57,283
One day, I'm going to be somebody.

558
00:38:57,367 --> 00:38:59,164
That's right. He's going to be mayor.

559
00:38:59,247 --> 00:39:00,566
Yeah, I'm...

560
00:39:01,207 --> 00:39:02,526
Mayor!

561
00:39:03,247 --> 00:39:07,001
Now that's a good idea!
I could run for mayor.

562
00:39:07,087 --> 00:39:10,716
- A colored mayor. That'll be the day.
- Wait and see. I will be mayor.

563
00:39:10,807 --> 00:39:13,082
I'll be the most powerful man
in Hill Valley...

564
00:39:13,167 --> 00:39:14,919
...and I'm going to clean up this town.

565
00:39:15,007 --> 00:39:17,521
Good. You can start by sweeping the floor.

566
00:39:20,287 --> 00:39:22,323
Mayor Goldie Wilson.

567
00:39:22,407 --> 00:39:24,238
I like the sound of that.

568
00:39:27,727 --> 00:39:29,240
[Bicycle bell rings]

569
00:39:36,247 --> 00:39:39,523
Hey, Dad! George! Hey, you on the bike!

570
00:40:09,527 --> 00:40:11,483
He's a peeping Tom!

571
00:40:16,927 --> 00:40:18,155
Dad!

572
00:40:18,287 --> 00:40:19,766
[Horn honking]

573
00:40:24,407 --> 00:40:26,125
[Dogs barking]

574
00:40:30,247 --> 00:40:32,363
Wait a minute. Who are you?

575
00:40:34,087 --> 00:40:38,205
Stella! Another one of these damn kids
jumped in front of my car!

576
00:40:39,167 --> 00:40:41,727
<i>Come out here!</i>
<i>Help me take him in the house!</i>

577
00:40:44,167 --> 00:40:46,158
[Thunder rumbling]

578
00:40:47,047 --> 00:40:48,446
Mom?

579
00:40:48,607 --> 00:40:50,086
<i>That you?</i>

580
00:40:50,407 --> 00:40:51,840
LORRAINE: There, there, now.

581
00:40:52,087 --> 00:40:53,440
<i>Just relax.</i>

582
00:40:55,847 --> 00:40:58,407
<i>You've been asleep</i>
<i>for almost nine hours now.</i>

583
00:41:00,527 --> 00:41:02,882
I had a horrible nightmare.

584
00:41:03,887 --> 00:41:06,879
I dreamed that I went back in time.

585
00:41:07,287 --> 00:41:08,561
<i>It was terrible.</i>

586
00:41:09,287 --> 00:41:10,561
LORRAINE: Well...

587
00:41:10,967 --> 00:41:14,323
...you're safe and sound now
back in good old 1955.

588
00:41:15,487 --> 00:41:16,840
1955?

589
00:41:20,367 --> 00:41:21,356
[Marty gasping]

590
00:41:21,447 --> 00:41:23,961
You're my...

591
00:41:24,167 --> 00:41:25,998
My name is Lorraine.

592
00:41:26,247 --> 00:41:29,045
LORRAINE: Lorraine Baines?
MARTY: Yeah.

593
00:41:30,047 --> 00:41:31,526
But you're...

594
00:41:31,607 --> 00:41:33,040
You're so...

595
00:41:33,127 --> 00:41:36,324
You're so thin!

596
00:41:36,407 --> 00:41:39,399
Just relax, Calvin.
You got a big bruise on your head.

597
00:41:40,047 --> 00:41:41,639
[Panting]

598
00:41:42,127 --> 00:41:43,355
[Marty exclaiming]

599
00:41:43,647 --> 00:41:45,285
Where are my pants?

600
00:41:45,527 --> 00:41:46,960
Over there...

601
00:41:47,487 --> 00:41:49,045
...on my hope chest.

602
00:41:50,407 --> 00:41:53,126
I've never seen
purple underwear before, Calvin.

603
00:41:53,487 --> 00:41:56,365
Calvin?
Why do you keep calling me Calvin?

604
00:41:56,447 --> 00:41:59,086
That is your name, isn't it? Calvin Klein.

605
00:41:59,567 --> 00:42:01,797
It's written all over your underwear.

606
00:42:02,687 --> 00:42:04,996
I guess they call you Cal, huh?

607
00:42:05,327 --> 00:42:07,045
No, actually, people...

608
00:42:07,727 --> 00:42:09,240
...call me Marty.

609
00:42:09,367 --> 00:42:10,516
[Sighing]

610
00:42:10,887 --> 00:42:12,764
Pleased to meet you, Calvin...

611
00:42:14,087 --> 00:42:15,406
Marty...

612
00:42:16,767 --> 00:42:17,961
...Klein.

613
00:42:24,447 --> 00:42:27,598
- Do you mind if I sit here?
- No. Fine.

614
00:42:27,727 --> 00:42:30,161
No. Good. Fine. Good.

615
00:42:31,927 --> 00:42:34,441
That's a big bruise you have there.

616
00:42:34,607 --> 00:42:35,596
[Marty shouts]

617
00:42:35,687 --> 00:42:37,917
STELLA: Lorraine, are you up there?

618
00:42:38,007 --> 00:42:39,838
Oh, my God! It's my mother!

619
00:42:39,967 --> 00:42:42,845
LORRAINE:
Quick! Put your pants back on!

620
00:42:50,767 --> 00:42:52,997
STELLA:
Marty, how long have you been in port?

621
00:42:53,087 --> 00:42:55,442
MARTY: Excuse me?
STELLA: I guessed you're a sailor.

622
00:42:55,527 --> 00:42:57,882
That's why you wear that life preserver.

623
00:42:58,007 --> 00:42:59,326
Coast guard.

624
00:42:59,407 --> 00:43:03,605
Sam, here's the young man you hit
with your car. He's all right. Thank God.

625
00:43:03,687 --> 00:43:05,882
What were you doing
in the middle of the street?

626
00:43:05,967 --> 00:43:08,561
Don't pay attention to him.
He's in one of his moods.

627
00:43:08,647 --> 00:43:11,366
Quit fiddling with that thing.
Come in here to dinner.

628
00:43:11,447 --> 00:43:13,278
STELLA: You already know Lorraine.

629
00:43:13,367 --> 00:43:15,323
This is Milton, this is Sally...

630
00:43:15,407 --> 00:43:19,446
...that's Toby, and over there
in the playpen is little baby Joey.

631
00:43:21,367 --> 00:43:23,278
MARTY: So, you're my uncle Joey.

632
00:43:24,127 --> 00:43:26,436
Better get used to these bars, kid.

633
00:43:26,527 --> 00:43:30,566
STELLA:
Yes. Joey just loves being in his playpen.

634
00:43:30,687 --> 00:43:34,157
He cries whenever we take him out,
so we leave him in there all the time.

635
00:43:34,247 --> 00:43:36,556
Well, Marty, I hope you like meat loaf.

636
00:43:36,807 --> 00:43:39,605
- Well, listen, I really ought to...
- Sit here, Marty.

637
00:43:40,367 --> 00:43:44,599
Sam, stop fiddling with that thing
and come in here and eat your dinner.

638
00:43:44,807 --> 00:43:46,206
[Sam chortling]

639
00:43:46,327 --> 00:43:47,999
Look at it roll.

640
00:43:48,087 --> 00:43:50,999
Now we can watch
Jackie Gleason while we eat.

641
00:43:56,327 --> 00:43:58,443
[Muffled voices on TV]

642
00:43:58,727 --> 00:44:02,083
Our first television set.
Dad just picked it up today.

643
00:44:02,847 --> 00:44:04,485
Do you have a television?

644
00:44:04,927 --> 00:44:07,680
Well, yeah.
You know, we have two of them.

645
00:44:07,807 --> 00:44:10,446
Wow! You must be rich.

646
00:44:10,527 --> 00:44:14,839
Honey, he's teasing you.
Nobody has two television sets.

647
00:44:19,167 --> 00:44:20,156
[Marty exclaiming]

648
00:44:20,247 --> 00:44:23,045
I've seen this one. This is a classic.

649
00:44:23,127 --> 00:44:26,005
This is where Ralph dresses up
as a man from space.

650
00:44:26,247 --> 00:44:29,319
What do you mean, you've seen this?
It's brand-new.

651
00:44:29,607 --> 00:44:32,121
Yeah, well, I saw it on a rerun.

652
00:44:32,567 --> 00:44:34,125
What's a rerun?

653
00:44:34,407 --> 00:44:35,840
You'll find out.

654
00:44:35,927 --> 00:44:38,157
You know, Marty,
you look so familiar to me.

655
00:44:38,247 --> 00:44:40,124
Do I know your mother?

656
00:44:41,287 --> 00:44:43,198
Yeah, I think maybe you do.

657
00:44:43,327 --> 00:44:46,524
STELLA: Then I'll call her.
I don't want her to worry about you.

658
00:44:46,607 --> 00:44:47,756
You can't.

659
00:44:47,887 --> 00:44:52,005
[Stuttering]
That is, nobody's home.

660
00:44:54,407 --> 00:44:55,760
Yet.

661
00:44:57,807 --> 00:44:58,956
Listen.

662
00:44:59,047 --> 00:45:01,515
Do you know where Riverside Drive is?

663
00:45:01,607 --> 00:45:05,395
It's on the other end of town.
A block past Maple. East end of town.

664
00:45:05,647 --> 00:45:08,844
A block past Maple.
That's John F. Kennedy Drive.

665
00:45:10,287 --> 00:45:12,198
Who the hell is John F. Kennedy?

666
00:45:12,287 --> 00:45:13,686
LORRAINE: Mother?

667
00:45:14,127 --> 00:45:16,641
<i>With Marty's parents out of town...</i>

668
00:45:17,167 --> 00:45:19,476
...don't you think
he ought to spend the night?

669
00:45:19,567 --> 00:45:21,876
After all,
Dad almost killed him with the car.

670
00:45:21,967 --> 00:45:23,878
That's true, Marty.

671
00:45:24,047 --> 00:45:27,596
I think you should spend the night.
I think you're our responsibility.

672
00:45:27,687 --> 00:45:30,997
- Well, gee, I don't know.
- He can sleep in my room.

673
00:45:31,287 --> 00:45:32,845
MARTY: I got to go!

674
00:45:33,127 --> 00:45:35,243
Thanks very much. You were all great.

675
00:45:35,327 --> 00:45:36,726
See you all later.

676
00:45:37,847 --> 00:45:39,280
Much later.

677
00:45:39,967 --> 00:45:41,320
[Door closes]

678
00:45:43,087 --> 00:45:45,601
He's a very strange young man.

679
00:45:45,767 --> 00:45:47,086
He's an idiot.

680
00:45:47,247 --> 00:45:50,478
<i>Comes from upbringing.</i>
<i>His parents are probably idiots, too.</i>

681
00:45:51,167 --> 00:45:54,682
<i>Lorraine, you ever have a kid</i>
<i>who acts that way, I'll disown you.</i>

682
00:46:16,327 --> 00:46:17,760
[Knocking on door]

683
00:46:24,927 --> 00:46:26,519
[Electronic warbling]

684
00:46:31,127 --> 00:46:32,480
MARTY: Doc?

685
00:46:33,047 --> 00:46:34,560
Don't say a word.

686
00:46:35,767 --> 00:46:38,201
DOC: No names. I want
to know nothing about you.

687
00:46:38,287 --> 00:46:39,800
MARTY: Listen, Doc...
DOC: Quiet!

688
00:46:39,887 --> 00:46:41,479
DOC: Don't tell me anything.

689
00:46:41,567 --> 00:46:43,603
MARTY: You got to help...
DOC: Quiet.

690
00:46:43,727 --> 00:46:45,763
[Electronic warbling]

691
00:46:46,127 --> 00:46:48,004
I'm going to read your thoughts.

692
00:46:48,127 --> 00:46:51,563
Let's see now.
You come here from a great distance?

693
00:46:51,647 --> 00:46:54,002
- Yeah. Exactly.
- Don't tell me!

694
00:46:54,527 --> 00:46:57,246
DOC: You want me to subscribe
to the <i>Saturday Evening Post</i>.

695
00:46:57,327 --> 00:46:59,795
- No.
- Not a word now!

696
00:46:59,887 --> 00:47:01,002
Quiet.

697
00:47:03,087 --> 00:47:04,361
Donations.

698
00:47:04,447 --> 00:47:06,403
You want me to make a donation...

699
00:47:06,487 --> 00:47:08,762
...to the Coast Guard Youth Auxiliary.

700
00:47:09,327 --> 00:47:10,646
Doc...

701
00:47:10,767 --> 00:47:12,041
[Electronics grow silent]

702
00:47:12,127 --> 00:47:14,163
...l'm from the future.

703
00:47:14,247 --> 00:47:17,125
I came here in a time machine
that you invented.

704
00:47:17,607 --> 00:47:22,158
Now, I need your help
to get back to the year 1985.

705
00:47:23,527 --> 00:47:24,846
My God!

706
00:47:29,287 --> 00:47:31,403
Do you know what this means?

707
00:47:33,007 --> 00:47:37,125
It means that
this damn thing doesn't work at all!

708
00:47:37,207 --> 00:47:41,405
MARTY: You got to help me. You are the only
one who knows how your time machine works.

709
00:47:41,487 --> 00:47:42,886
[Whispering] Time machine?

710
00:47:43,407 --> 00:47:45,523
I haven't invented any time machine.

711
00:47:46,967 --> 00:47:48,923
Okay. I'll prove it to you.

712
00:47:49,367 --> 00:47:52,439
Look at my driver's license. Expires 1987.

713
00:47:52,527 --> 00:47:55,963
Look at my birthday.
I haven't even been born yet.

714
00:47:56,047 --> 00:47:58,003
And look at this picture.

715
00:47:58,207 --> 00:48:00,277
It's my brother, my sister and me.

716
00:48:00,367 --> 00:48:03,518
Look at her sweatshirt, Doc.
<i>"</i>Class of 1984<i>"</i>?

717
00:48:04,407 --> 00:48:08,286
DOC: Pretty mediocre photographic fakery.
They cut off your brother's hair.

718
00:48:09,127 --> 00:48:11,402
I'm telling the truth.
You got to believe me.

719
00:48:11,487 --> 00:48:14,206
Then tell me, future boy...

720
00:48:14,607 --> 00:48:18,520
...who's president of the United States
in 1985?

721
00:48:18,607 --> 00:48:21,963
- Ronald Reagan.
- Ronald Reagan? The actor?

722
00:48:22,087 --> 00:48:23,361
[Doc exclaims]

723
00:48:23,487 --> 00:48:25,921
Then who's vice president? Jerry Lewis?

724
00:48:27,047 --> 00:48:30,403
DOC: I suppose Jane Wyman is the First Lady.
MARTY: Wait, Doc!

725
00:48:30,487 --> 00:48:32,603
DOC: And Jack Benny is treasury secretary.

726
00:48:32,687 --> 00:48:33,961
MARTY: Listen to me.

727
00:48:34,087 --> 00:48:37,363
I've had enough jokes for one evening.
Good night, future boy!

728
00:48:37,447 --> 00:48:38,721
MARTY: No, wait, Doc.

729
00:48:38,807 --> 00:48:42,959
MARTY: The bruise on your head.
I know how that happened. You told me.

730
00:48:43,047 --> 00:48:45,515
You were standing on your toilet
hanging a clock...

731
00:48:45,607 --> 00:48:47,723
...and you fell
and hit your head on the sink.

732
00:48:47,807 --> 00:48:51,402
That's when you got the idea
for the flux capacitor which...

733
00:48:51,487 --> 00:48:54,559
...is what makes time travel possible.

734
00:48:59,047 --> 00:49:01,038
[Mysterious instrumental music]

735
00:49:07,087 --> 00:49:11,080
MARTY: There's something wrong with
the starter, so I hid it here.

736
00:49:21,167 --> 00:49:23,044
DOC: After I fell off my toilet...

737
00:49:24,047 --> 00:49:25,366
<i>... I drew this.</i>

738
00:49:29,167 --> 00:49:30,600
MARTY: The flux capacitor.

739
00:49:39,687 --> 00:49:41,166
[Electric crackling]

740
00:49:48,007 --> 00:49:49,406
It works!

741
00:49:49,767 --> 00:49:51,485
[Doc laughing]

742
00:49:51,687 --> 00:49:53,166
It works!

743
00:49:54,407 --> 00:49:56,682
I finally invent something that works!

744
00:49:57,727 --> 00:49:59,558
You bet your ass it works.

745
00:50:00,767 --> 00:50:03,327
We've got to sneak this back
to my laboratory.

746
00:50:03,647 --> 00:50:05,478
We've got to get you home!

747
00:50:06,127 --> 00:50:07,560
This is it.

748
00:50:09,607 --> 00:50:11,563
DOC ON TV:
<i>Never mind that now.</i>

749
00:50:11,647 --> 00:50:13,956
DOC: Why, that's me! Look at me!

750
00:50:14,127 --> 00:50:16,163
- I'm an old man!
<i>- I'm Dr. Emmett Brown.</i>

751
00:50:16,247 --> 00:50:18,203
<i>I'm in the Twin Pines Mall parking lot.</i>

752
00:50:18,287 --> 00:50:20,278
Thank God, I've still got my hair.

753
00:50:20,367 --> 00:50:22,278
What's this thing I'm wearing?

754
00:50:22,367 --> 00:50:24,437
This is a radiation suit.

755
00:50:24,527 --> 00:50:26,199
Radiation suit?

756
00:50:26,287 --> 00:50:29,484
Of course. 'Cause of all the fallout
from the atomic wars.

757
00:50:30,447 --> 00:50:33,325
This is truly amazing.

758
00:50:33,487 --> 00:50:35,955
A portable television studio.

759
00:50:36,247 --> 00:50:39,922
No wonder your president has to be
an actor. He has to look good on TV.

760
00:50:40,007 --> 00:50:41,838
MARTY: This is the part coming up.

761
00:50:43,007 --> 00:50:47,159
<i>This sucker's electrical but I need a nuclear</i>
<i>reaction to generate the 1.21 gigawatts...</i>

762
00:50:47,247 --> 00:50:49,124
What did I just say?

763
00:50:52,367 --> 00:50:55,359
<i>... this sucker's electrical,</i>
<i>but I need a nuclear reaction...</i>

764
00:50:55,447 --> 00:50:59,201
<i>...to generate the 1.21 gigawatts of...</i>
- 1.21 gigawatts!

765
00:51:00,567 --> 00:51:02,603
1.21 gigawatts.

766
00:51:04,647 --> 00:51:06,160
DOC: Great Scott!

767
00:51:08,287 --> 00:51:10,721
What the hell is a gigawatt?

768
00:51:11,367 --> 00:51:13,403
How could I have been so careless?

769
00:51:13,487 --> 00:51:15,284
1.21 gigawatts!

770
00:51:15,367 --> 00:51:17,927
Tom, how am I going to generate
that kind of power?

771
00:51:18,007 --> 00:51:19,486
It can't be done, can it?

772
00:51:19,567 --> 00:51:22,877
MARTY: Doc, look.
All we need is a little plutonium.

773
00:51:23,447 --> 00:51:27,326
DOC: I'm sure that in 1985 plutonium is
available in every corner drugstore...

774
00:51:27,407 --> 00:51:30,046
...but in 1955, it's a little hard to come by.

775
00:51:30,127 --> 00:51:33,005
Marty, I'm sorry,
but I'm afraid you're stuck here.

776
00:51:34,607 --> 00:51:36,598
Doc, stuck here? I can't be stuck here.

777
00:51:36,687 --> 00:51:38,837
I got a life in 1985.

778
00:51:38,927 --> 00:51:40,918
- I got a girl.
- Is she pretty?

779
00:51:41,527 --> 00:51:43,040
Doc, she's beautiful.

780
00:51:43,887 --> 00:51:45,957
She's crazy about me. Look at this.

781
00:51:46,287 --> 00:51:48,118
<i>Look what she wrote here.</i>

782
00:51:48,367 --> 00:51:50,005
<i>That says it all.</i>

783
00:51:50,767 --> 00:51:53,327
Doc, you're my only hope.

784
00:51:53,847 --> 00:51:57,078
Marty, I'm sorry, but the only power source
capable of generating...

785
00:51:57,167 --> 00:52:00,239
...1.21 gigawatts of electricity
is a bolt of lightning.

786
00:52:01,607 --> 00:52:03,837
MARTY: What did you say?
DOC: A bolt of lightning.

787
00:52:03,927 --> 00:52:07,556
Unfortunately, you never know
when or where it's ever going to strike.

788
00:52:09,447 --> 00:52:10,562
We do now.

789
00:52:15,647 --> 00:52:16,762
This is it!

790
00:52:17,447 --> 00:52:19,597
This is the answer.

791
00:52:19,807 --> 00:52:22,082
It says here that a bolt of lightning...

792
00:52:22,167 --> 00:52:26,319
...is going to strike the clock tower
at 10:04 p.m. Next Saturday night!

793
00:52:29,767 --> 00:52:33,077
If we could somehow harness
this lightning...

794
00:52:34,207 --> 00:52:37,404
...channel it into the flux capacitor...

795
00:52:38,647 --> 00:52:40,080
<i>... it just might work.</i>

796
00:52:40,647 --> 00:52:44,606
Next Saturday night
we're sending you back to the future!

797
00:52:45,527 --> 00:52:47,324
All right. Saturday's good.

798
00:52:47,407 --> 00:52:51,082
I can spend a week in 1955.
I can hang out. You can show me around.

799
00:52:51,407 --> 00:52:54,126
That is out of the question.
You must not leave this house.

800
00:52:54,207 --> 00:52:56,118
You must not see or talk to anybody.

801
00:52:56,207 --> 00:53:00,359
Anything you do can have repercussions
on future events. Do you understand?

802
00:53:01,287 --> 00:53:03,118
Yeah. Sure. Okay.

803
00:53:03,767 --> 00:53:05,120
Marty...

804
00:53:05,327 --> 00:53:08,364
...have you interacted with anybody else
today besides me?

805
00:53:10,327 --> 00:53:13,364
Yeah, well, I might've sort of
bumped into my parents.

806
00:53:13,447 --> 00:53:16,803
Great Scott! Let me see that photograph
again of your brother.

807
00:53:20,447 --> 00:53:23,917
Just as I thought. This proves my theory.
Look at your brother.

808
00:53:24,927 --> 00:53:27,999
MARTY:
His head's gone. It's like it's been erased.

809
00:53:29,607 --> 00:53:31,563
Erased from existence.

810
00:53:37,007 --> 00:53:39,601
They really cleaned this place up.
Looks brand-new.

811
00:53:39,687 --> 00:53:42,997
DOC: According to my theory, you interfered
with your parents' first meeting.

812
00:53:43,087 --> 00:53:46,238
If they don't meet, they won't fall in love,
get married or have kids.

813
00:53:46,327 --> 00:53:48,557
That's why your brother's disappearing.

814
00:53:48,647 --> 00:53:52,003
Your sister will follow, and unless
you repair the damage, you're next.

815
00:53:52,087 --> 00:53:54,920
MARTY: Sounds heavy.
DOC: Weight has nothing to do with it.

816
00:53:55,007 --> 00:53:56,486
Which one's your pop?

817
00:53:56,567 --> 00:53:57,841
[Bell ringing]

818
00:53:57,927 --> 00:53:59,042
That's him.

819
00:53:59,647 --> 00:54:01,797
Okay. Okay, you guys.

820
00:54:01,927 --> 00:54:03,485
[George pretending to laugh]

821
00:54:03,567 --> 00:54:06,639
Very funny.
You guys are being real mature.

822
00:54:06,767 --> 00:54:08,519
Maybe you were adopted.

823
00:54:08,607 --> 00:54:11,041
GEORGE: Okay, real mature, guys.

824
00:54:11,927 --> 00:54:14,361
GEORGE: Okay, pick up my books.
STRICKLAND: McFly.

825
00:54:14,447 --> 00:54:15,846
That's Strickland.

826
00:54:16,527 --> 00:54:18,518
Jesus, didn't that guy ever have hair?

827
00:54:18,607 --> 00:54:21,041
Shape up, man. You're a slacker.

828
00:54:21,287 --> 00:54:24,199
Do you want to be a slacker
for the rest of your life?

829
00:54:24,327 --> 00:54:25,237
No.

830
00:54:25,687 --> 00:54:28,406
- What did your mother see in him?
- I don't know.

831
00:54:28,567 --> 00:54:32,196
I guess she felt sorry for him
'cause her dad hit him with the car.

832
00:54:32,807 --> 00:54:34,957
He hit me with the car.

833
00:54:35,047 --> 00:54:36,958
That's the Florence Nightingale effect.

834
00:54:37,047 --> 00:54:40,437
It happens in hospitals when
nurses fall in love with their patients.

835
00:54:40,527 --> 00:54:41,721
Go to it, kid.

836
00:54:43,167 --> 00:54:45,237
George, buddy.

837
00:54:45,607 --> 00:54:47,882
I have been looking all over for you.

838
00:54:47,967 --> 00:54:51,198
You remember me,
the guy who saved your life the other day?

839
00:54:52,007 --> 00:54:54,965
- Yeah.
- There's somebody I'd like you to meet.

840
00:54:59,247 --> 00:55:00,362
Lorraine?

841
00:55:01,127 --> 00:55:02,321
Calvin!

842
00:55:03,287 --> 00:55:05,926
I'd like you to meet
my good friend George McFly.

843
00:55:06,007 --> 00:55:09,158
Hi. It's really a pleasure to meet you.

844
00:55:10,287 --> 00:55:12,755
- How's your head?
- Good. Fine.

845
00:55:13,087 --> 00:55:16,363
I've been worried about you
ever since you ran off the other night.

846
00:55:16,447 --> 00:55:17,721
Are you okay?

847
00:55:17,807 --> 00:55:19,001
[Bell ringing]

848
00:55:19,087 --> 00:55:21,442
- I'm sorry. I have to go.
- Come on!

849
00:55:22,327 --> 00:55:24,045
Isn't he a dreamboat?

850
00:55:28,047 --> 00:55:31,198
- She didn't even look at him.
- This is more serious than I thought.

851
00:55:31,287 --> 00:55:34,279
Your mother is infatuated with you
instead of your father.

852
00:55:35,327 --> 00:55:36,442
Wait a minute, Doc.

853
00:55:36,527 --> 00:55:39,997
Are you trying to tell me
that my mother has got the hots for me?

854
00:55:40,087 --> 00:55:42,601
- Precisely.
- This is heavy.

855
00:55:42,807 --> 00:55:44,798
There's that word again. <i>"</i>Heavy.<i>"</i>

856
00:55:44,887 --> 00:55:48,926
Why are things so heavy in the future?
Is there a problem with the Earth's gravity?

857
00:55:49,007 --> 00:55:52,204
The only way we're going to
get them to mate is if they're alone.

858
00:55:52,287 --> 00:55:54,596
You've got to get them to interact...

859
00:55:54,887 --> 00:55:56,878
...in some sort of social...

860
00:55:58,167 --> 00:56:00,362
- You mean like a date?
- Right!

861
00:56:00,927 --> 00:56:03,521
What kind of date?
What do kids do in the '50s?

862
00:56:04,127 --> 00:56:06,197
They're your parents.
You must know them.

863
00:56:06,287 --> 00:56:09,882
What are their common interests?
What do they like to do together?

864
00:56:10,247 --> 00:56:11,282
Nothing.

865
00:56:11,367 --> 00:56:14,359
DOC: Look! There's a rhythmic
ceremonial ritual coming up.

866
00:56:14,527 --> 00:56:17,803
The Enchantment Under the Sea dance!
They're supposed to go to this.

867
00:56:17,887 --> 00:56:20,799
- That's where they kiss for the first time.
- All right, kid.

868
00:56:20,887 --> 00:56:24,482
You stick to your father like glue
and make sure he takes her to that dance.

869
00:56:24,847 --> 00:56:26,644
MARTY: George, buddy...

870
00:56:27,047 --> 00:56:30,164
...remember that girl
I introduced you to, Lorraine?

871
00:56:35,967 --> 00:56:37,605
What are you writing?

872
00:56:38,727 --> 00:56:39,921
Stories.

873
00:56:40,367 --> 00:56:43,916
MR. MCFLY: Science fiction stories
about visitors...

874
00:56:44,207 --> 00:56:47,279
...coming down to Earth
from other planets.

875
00:56:49,247 --> 00:56:52,762
Get out of town!
I didn't know you did anything creative.

876
00:56:53,247 --> 00:56:55,920
- Let me read some.
- No, no.

877
00:56:56,007 --> 00:56:58,805
I never let anybody read my stories.

878
00:56:59,447 --> 00:57:00,766
MARTY: Why not?

879
00:57:01,887 --> 00:57:05,482
What if they didn't like them?
What if they told me I was no good?

880
00:57:07,327 --> 00:57:10,683
I guess that would be pretty hard
for somebody to understand.

881
00:57:11,367 --> 00:57:13,835
No. No, not hard at all.

882
00:57:15,007 --> 00:57:17,475
So anyway, George. About Lorraine.

883
00:57:18,567 --> 00:57:20,080
She really likes you.

884
00:57:21,247 --> 00:57:23,886
She told me to tell you
that she wants you to ask her...

885
00:57:23,967 --> 00:57:25,844
...to the Enchantment
Under the Sea dance.

886
00:57:25,927 --> 00:57:26,882
- Really?
- Yeah.

887
00:57:27,127 --> 00:57:29,846
All you got to do is go over there
and ask her.

888
00:57:30,967 --> 00:57:33,083
Right here, right now, in the cafeteria?

889
00:57:33,167 --> 00:57:36,682
What if she said no? I don't know
if I could take that kind of rejection.

890
00:57:38,327 --> 00:57:42,115
Besides, I think she'd rather go
with somebody else.

891
00:57:43,367 --> 00:57:44,482
MARTY: Who?

892
00:57:46,327 --> 00:57:47,282
Biff.

893
00:57:48,767 --> 00:57:51,156
- Don't kid around. Come on.
- Come on. Leave.

894
00:57:51,247 --> 00:57:53,124
BIFF: You know you want it.

895
00:57:53,207 --> 00:57:55,118
You know you want me to give it to you.

896
00:57:55,207 --> 00:57:58,005
Shut your filthy mouth.
I'm not that kind of girl.

897
00:57:58,887 --> 00:58:01,447
Maybe you are
and you just don't know it yet.

898
00:58:01,687 --> 00:58:03,359
Get your meat hooks off of me.

899
00:58:03,447 --> 00:58:06,245
MARTY: You heard her.
She said, get your meat hooks...

900
00:58:06,927 --> 00:58:07,882
...off.

901
00:58:09,167 --> 00:58:10,282
MARTY: Please.

902
00:58:11,127 --> 00:58:12,879
What's it to you, butthead?

903
00:58:14,207 --> 00:58:16,198
BIFF: You been looking for a fight.

904
00:58:16,367 --> 00:58:17,800
[People exclaiming]

905
00:58:25,887 --> 00:58:28,879
Since you're new here,
I'm going to cut you a break...

906
00:58:29,327 --> 00:58:30,362
...today.

907
00:58:31,527 --> 00:58:33,882
So why don't you make like a tree...

908
00:58:34,087 --> 00:58:35,645
...and get out of here.

909
00:58:43,207 --> 00:58:44,640
[Boy laughing]

910
00:58:47,287 --> 00:58:47,878
MARTY: George!

911
00:58:49,847 --> 00:58:51,724
GEORGE: Why do you keep following me?

912
00:58:51,807 --> 00:58:56,403
George, I'm telling you,
if you do not ask Lorraine to that dance...

913
00:58:56,487 --> 00:58:59,399
...l'll regret it for the rest of my life.
- I can't go.

914
00:58:59,487 --> 00:59:02,524
I'll miss my favorite TV program,
<i>Science Fiction Theatre</i>.

915
00:59:02,607 --> 00:59:05,804
Yeah, but Lorraine wants to go with you.

916
00:59:06,007 --> 00:59:07,486
Give her a break.

917
00:59:07,807 --> 00:59:11,197
I'm just not ready
to ask Lorraine out to the dance...

918
00:59:11,807 --> 00:59:14,719
...and not you
or anybody else on this planet...

919
00:59:14,967 --> 00:59:17,083
...is going to make me change my mind.

920
00:59:23,967 --> 00:59:25,798
MARTY: <i>Science Fiction Theatre</i>.

921
00:59:39,727 --> 00:59:41,046
[Muffled breathing]

922
00:59:48,287 --> 00:59:49,800
[Loud rock music plays]

923
00:59:53,567 --> 00:59:55,125
[Stops music]

924
00:59:56,207 --> 00:59:57,356
Who are you?

925
00:59:57,447 --> 00:59:58,926
[Plays music]

926
01:00:01,447 --> 01:00:02,436
[Stops music]

927
01:00:02,527 --> 01:00:04,518
MARTY: [Muffled] <i>Silence, Earthling.</i>

928
01:00:05,887 --> 01:00:08,242
<i>My name is Darth Vader.</i>

929
01:00:13,087 --> 01:00:16,397
<i>I am an extraterrestrial</i>
<i>from the planet Vulcan.</i>

930
01:00:18,447 --> 01:00:19,402
Marty!

931
01:00:19,527 --> 01:00:21,085
[Car honks]

932
01:00:22,567 --> 01:00:24,683
- Marty! Marty!
- George, buddy.

933
01:00:24,767 --> 01:00:27,076
You weren't at school.
What have you been doing?

934
01:00:27,167 --> 01:00:29,965
I overslept. I need your help.

935
01:00:30,047 --> 01:00:32,925
I have to ask Lorraine out,
but I don't know how to do it.

936
01:00:33,007 --> 01:00:35,362
Keep your pants on. She's over in the cafe.

937
01:00:35,447 --> 01:00:37,403
God! How do you...?

938
01:00:40,127 --> 01:00:41,765
MARTY: What made you change your mind?

939
01:00:41,847 --> 01:00:44,645
Last night, Darth Vader came down
from planet Vulcan...

940
01:00:44,727 --> 01:00:48,481
...and told me that if I didn't
take Lorraine out, he'd melt my brain.

941
01:00:48,567 --> 01:00:51,525
Let's just keep this brain-melting stuff
to ourselves, okay?

942
01:00:51,607 --> 01:00:54,758
- Yeah. Yeah.
- All right. There she is.

943
01:00:55,047 --> 01:00:56,765
Just go in there and invite her.

944
01:00:56,847 --> 01:00:59,441
GEORGE: But I don't know what to say.
MARTY: Say anything.

945
01:00:59,527 --> 01:01:02,917
Say whatever's natural,
the first thing that comes into your mind.

946
01:01:04,007 --> 01:01:05,838
Nothing's coming to my mind.

947
01:01:05,927 --> 01:01:07,997
Jesus. It's a wonder I was even born.

948
01:01:08,087 --> 01:01:10,555
- What? What?
- Nothing.

949
01:01:11,967 --> 01:01:14,561
Tell her destiny brought you together.

950
01:01:14,647 --> 01:01:18,356
Tell her she is the most beautiful girl
you have ever seen in the world.

951
01:01:18,447 --> 01:01:20,005
Girls like that stuff.

952
01:01:20,647 --> 01:01:23,719
- What are you doing?
- I'm writing this down. This is good stuff.

953
01:01:23,807 --> 01:01:26,765
- Yeah. Okay. Can you take care of that?
- Right.

954
01:01:27,127 --> 01:01:28,879
[<i>The Wallflower</i> playing]

955
01:01:29,007 --> 01:01:30,725
[People chattering]

956
01:01:44,167 --> 01:01:46,806
Lou, give me a milk.

957
01:01:48,287 --> 01:01:49,356
Chocolate.

958
01:02:05,127 --> 01:02:06,321
GEORGE: Lorraine.

959
01:02:06,887 --> 01:02:08,161
My density...

960
01:02:08,807 --> 01:02:10,638
...has popped me to you.

961
01:02:11,327 --> 01:02:12,476
What?

962
01:02:12,647 --> 01:02:14,000
[Mumbling]

963
01:02:14,487 --> 01:02:17,047
What I meant to say was...

964
01:02:17,167 --> 01:02:19,806
Wait a minute.
Don't I know you from somewhere?

965
01:02:20,487 --> 01:02:21,556
GEORGE: Yes.

966
01:02:21,847 --> 01:02:25,601
Yes. I'm George. George McFly.

967
01:02:26,207 --> 01:02:27,799
I'm your density.

968
01:02:28,767 --> 01:02:29,961
I mean...

969
01:02:31,367 --> 01:02:32,595
...your destiny.

970
01:02:33,807 --> 01:02:35,126
[Sighing]

971
01:02:35,927 --> 01:02:36,803
BIFF: McFly.

972
01:02:38,647 --> 01:02:40,399
[Music stops]

973
01:02:41,207 --> 01:02:43,721
I thought I told you never to come in here.

974
01:02:46,447 --> 01:02:48,165
Well, it's going to cost you.

975
01:02:48,887 --> 01:02:50,798
How much money you got on you?

976
01:02:51,367 --> 01:02:53,119
GEORGE: How much do you want, Biff?

977
01:02:53,207 --> 01:02:54,401
[Biff grunts]

978
01:02:54,487 --> 01:02:56,478
[All gasping]

979
01:03:01,327 --> 01:03:02,680
BIFF: All right, punk.

980
01:03:02,887 --> 01:03:05,196
- Now I'm going to...
- Biff. What's that?

981
